<DOC><DOCNO> AP880608-0092 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-08-88 0830EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Self-Immolation     06-08 0317</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Soviet-Self-Immolation,0326</SECOND><HEAD>Woman Who Doused Herself Near Kremlin Wall Dies</HEAD><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A woman who doused herself with gasoline and setherself on on fire by the Kremlin wall died after a difficult lifeas an orphan and former mental patient, a newspaper reported today.   Moscow News, a weekly paper, said Nadezhda Bannaya was burnedover 85 percent of her body and died Monday in a trauma institute.   Soviet officials had confirmed the fire on Friday.   The woman, who was 46, moved from city to city, frequentlychanging jobs, the newspaper said.   ``I heard an awful woman's scream,'' militiaman Oleg Zhmiryatold Moscow News, ``and immediately ran to her. On the way anotherworker joined me. The woman was already burning.''   The militiaman and the assistant put the woman on the lawn andbegan to stamp out the fire with their jackets and hats during theincident Friday, the newspaper said. A Kremlin worker brought anovercoat and put out the flames. The woman was taken to a hospital.   Maj. Valentin Kirsanov of the Red Square militia detachment toldMoscow News that a can, a pocketbook with a passport and workrecord book and notepad with prayers and a letter were found nearthe scene.   Bannaya came from a family of seven whose mother died early. Shewas brought up in an orphanage and lived mostly in the Ukrainemoving frequently and working as a maid and a cleaning woman, thenewspaper said.   A militia lieutenant told The Associated Press on Friday thereasons for the woman's action were not known. He said the incidentoccurred on the cobble esplanade between St. Basil's Cathedral andthe red brick wall surrounding the Kremlin.   Moscow News has been at the forefront of the Soviet leaderMikhail S. Gorbachev's campaign for greater openness on socialissues and its report of this incident was in line with that policy.</TEXT></DOC>